Ford GoBike¶

by Jeyan Çınar¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Ford GoBike is a bike sharing system powered both by Lyft and Ford in San Francisco Bay Area. Thousands of bikes to pick up and drop off anywhere - connecting people to work, friends and their favorite restaurant. Pocket friendly subscriptions and 24/7 available stations make it more compelling to ride. Unfortunately they're not in use anymore - it seems Lyft has pulled away from Ford's project due to some technical problems with the bikes themselves in 2019. But for the sake of this project I'll look into the data from February 2019 to see if I can spot any trends.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The data has 174952 entries and 13 rows. These include data in date & time, string and numeric formats.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • Start & end times indicate when the bike was picked up from & left at the station.
  • Similarly start & end station names are also given.
  • Bike IDs indicate the individual bike identifications.
  • User type indicates if the rider has a subscription or doesn't.
  • Member gender is the gender identifier of the rider.
  • Duration is the length of the trip in minutes.
  • Start & end weekdays indicate the name of the days the trip took place.
  • Similarly start & end hours indicate the time of the days.
  • Member age is calculated by extracting member's birth year given from the data set's year, 2019.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • I'm interested in trip durations - according to the descriptive statistics above, the average trip should be around 12 minutes; I'll dig deeper to see if there's any variation with categorical data.
  • The other numeric data is age - I'll take a look at its variations with categorical data as well.
  • I want to see how the different types of users affect the numerical values.
  • Gender distribution to the overall usage may also provide some insights.
  • Week days as categories may tell us which day exactly did these people choose to ride. Work days and weekends may tell different stories.
  • Hours of the day can also give a clue about the motive; school / work hours, leisure time, etc.
  • There are 329 stations - I wonder which ones were the busiest.

Both usual and log histograms still don't seem to tell much - I want to take a look at the exponential distribution as the log scale looks like the inverse of it. Here's the source of this function.

In [155]:
def exp_trans(x, inverse = False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.log(x)
    else:
        return np.exp(x)    

data = fordgo_v2['duration_min'];

bin_edges = np.arange(0, exp_trans(data.max())+0.5, 0.5);
tick_locs = np.arange(0, exp_trans(data.max())+2.5, 2.5);

sb.distplot(data.apply(exp_trans), bins = bin_edges, kde = False);

plt.xticks(tick_locs, exp_trans(tick_locs, inverse = True).astype(int));
plt.xlabel('Trip Duration in Minutes; Scaled to Exp');

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • There were some trips almost as long as a day since I wanted to take a look at shorter trips, I removed trips longer than 200 minutes.
  • I removed ages older than 90 as they were most likely incorrect entries.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • Ive applied exponential transformation to the trip durations as the data was too crowded in lower regions.
  • Logarithmic transformation gave a better distribution in age.
  • Ive proportioned user type and gender columns (separately) to see the relative frequencies among category types.
  • Ive ordered the categorical weekdays to make it more meaningful as a calendarized week.
  • Also proportioned weekdays, showed them with percentages for ease of reading.
  • Ive limited the list of stations to the top 5 for ease of interpretation. (but did not delete the rest from the data just for the sake of the graph).

def exp_trans(x, inverse = False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.log(x)
    else:
        return np.exp(x)    

duration_exp = fordgo_v2['duration_min']

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 5])

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • Distributions of age and trip durations dont have any correlation.
  • Variation around the mean trip duration of 12 minutes is larger in weekends people prefer shorter trips on work days.
  • Customers tend to have longer trips than subscribers (only by a couple of minutes).
  • Women seem to take longer trips than men, although the mean is still around 12 minutes.
  • People that take trips on weekends seem to have a slightly lower mean ageof 30, where the mean of working days is around 32 34.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  • Subscribers and customers have quite similar age distributions, still around the mean of 32.
  • Although the difference is not that significant, females seem to be a couple of years younger than men, having a tighter range of ages.
  • Working hours have a shorter range of trip durations, where 3 and 4 a.m. seem to have wider IQRs.
  • Mean age and variety is around 34 during working hours, but its interesting to see a peak of age 42 at 4 a.m.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Weekends seem to be more occupied by walk-in customers with longer trips up to 24 minutes. Subscribers seem to stick to a mean of 10 12 minutes every day.
  • Having slightly longer trips in the weekend is also observable with women, men and others - women and other to take longer trips by 2 - 3 minutes throughout the week.
  • Walk-in customers tend to take longer trips than sunscribers in general - the difference is more prominent during work hours, by 15 minutes.
  • Hour of the day doesn't seem to make as much of a difference (only 1 or 2 minutes) in different genders.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Unfortunately, no. Since I had only categorical and completely uncorrelated numeric data, it was hard to find out other aspects of the data set. This study can be expanded with additional information such as station capacities, customer occupations, route analyses or by collecting data from a larger time window.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

    which will convert mynotebook.ipynb to the default format (probably HTML).
    
    You can specify the export format with `--to`.
    Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides'].

    Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
    'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic' and 'full'. You
